  ## Environment Variables

  ### Frontend (Vercel)
  REACT_APP_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=     # Google Maps JS API key (browser-restricted)

  ### Backend (Railway)
  DATABASE_URL=                       # PostgreSQL connection string
  JWT_SECRET=                         # JWT signing secret
  GOOGLE_PLACES_API_KEY=              # Google Places API key (server-restricted)
  GOOGLE_GEMINI_API_KEY=              # Gemini API key (Birdie AI)
  WEATHER_API_KEY=                    # OpenWeatherMap API key
  BESTTIME_API_KEY=                   # BestTime foot traffic API
  TICKETMASTER_API_KEY=               # Ticketmaster Discovery API
  RESEND_API_KEY=                     # Resend email service
  PORT=5000                           # Server port
  NODE_ENV=production                 # Environment
  FRONTEND_URL=                       # Frontend origin for CORS

  ---

  ## Security

  - JWT authentication on all protected routes (24h token expiry)
  - bcrypt password hashing (salt rounds: 12)
  - Helmet.js HTTP security headers
  - CORS restricted to `flock-app*.vercel.app`
  - Rate limiting: 5/min on auth, 300/15min on API
  - Parameterized queries on every database call
  - Input validation via express-validator on all POST/PUT routes
  - XSS protection and input sanitization
  - Budget submissions are privacy-protected — individual amounts never leave the server

  ---

  ## Development

  ### Prerequisites
  - Node.js 18+
  - PostgreSQL 15+
  - Google Places API key
  - OpenWeatherMap API key (free tier)

  ### Local Setup
  ```bash
  # Clone
  git clone https://github.com/bansaljayden/Flock-app-.git
  cd Flock-app-

  # Backend
  cd backend
  npm install
  cp .env.example .env    # Fill in environment variables
  npm start               # Runs on port 5000

  # Frontend (separate terminal)
  cd frontend
  npm install
  cp .env.example .env    # Fill in Google Maps key
  npm start               # Runs on port 3000

  Database tables are created automatically on server startup via idempotent migrations.

  ---
  Architecture Decisions

  Why not Firebase/Supabase? PostgreSQL gives relational integrity for the complex relationships between users, flocks, venues, budgets, and votes. The data model is inherently relational.

  Why Socket.io over polling? Flock needs to feel alive. Instant message delivery, typing indicators, budget updates, and settlement notifications require persistent connections.

  Why a rule-based crowd engine + ML pipeline? The rule-based engine runs in under 50ms with zero API cost. The ML model (in development) will learn from real foot traffic data, weather patterns, and user
  feedback to improve accuracy over time. Both approaches coexist — the rule-based engine serves predictions now while the ML model trains on collected data.

  Why Venmo deep-links over Stripe? Zero transaction fees, zero regulatory exposure, zero payment processing liability. Stripe's 2.9% + $0.30 per transaction would exceed any viable fee structure. Flock
  calculates the split; Venmo moves the money.

  Why Gemini for the AI assistant? Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite offers function calling at low latency and cost. Birdie uses structured tool definitions to search venues, check crowds, and navigate the app — not just
   generate text.

